The defendant Eugenio Jimenez-Martinez was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 2nd-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Eugenio Jimenez-Martinez in court with attorney Martin Joseph Pruhs.  Defendant Eugenio Jimenez-Martinez in custody.  Thomas Potter for Francesco Mineo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sworn as Interpreter:  Brenda Bartholomew.   Defendant changes plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon he may no longer use or possess any firearms; also he may not vote in any election until his rights have been restored.  Court further advised that if he is not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon he may no longer use or possess any firearms or body armor; also he may not vote in any election until his civil rights have been restored.

 The Court sentenced defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Corrections, with credit for 123 days time served.  

-Court ordered defendant pay Court costs and all applicable assessments 
-Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the related surcharge 
-Defendant to pay Court costs, surcharges and all applicable assessments at the rate of $50.00 per month commencing on July 1, 2017 and to continue on the first day of each month thereafter until paid in full; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment
-Defendant to obtain an AODA assessment and cooperate with any treatment deemed appropriate

Defendant Eugenio Jiminez-Martinez in court.  Patrick Anderson and Francesco Mineo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Indigency hearing proceeded.  Atty Steve Sargent re-eformed defendant after he indicated that his employment changed, he is still not eligible.  Based upon the defendant's statements, the court found the defendant eligible for appointment of counsel at county expense.  The court appointed Attorney Andriusis to represent the defendant; Attorney Andriusis to be paid at the rate of $70.00 per hour.  The court ordered the defendant to repay Milwaukee County for attorney fees at the rate of $100.00 per month on or before the first day of every month commencing 07/01/2015. Failure to make timely payments according to the imposed payment schedule may result in a civil judgment, subject to tax intercept.  Order signed and filed.  Case adjourned for preliminary hearing in preliminary hearing court.  Preliminary hearing scheduled for June 5, 2015 at 08:30 am.
